     Immense and
								silent moon.

As the ranks returning, all worn and sweaty — as the men

     file by where I
							stand;

As the faces, the masks appear — as I glance at the faces,

     studying the
							masks;

How solemn the thought of my whispering soul, to each in

     the ranks, and to
							you;

Beautiful that war, and all its deeds of carnage, must in

     time be utterly
							lost;

To the fiery fields emanative, and the endless vistas beyond —

     to the south and
							the north;

We stand self-pois'd, in the middle, branching thence

     over the
								world;

Takes the lesson with calmness, perceives the corpse

     slowly borne
								from the house,

Through him flights, whirls, screams, answering those
of the fish-hawk, mocking-bird, night-heron,
and eagle;

The unsurvey'd interior, log-houses, clearings, wild

     animals,
								hunters, trappers;

Slavery — the murderous, treacherous conspiracy to

     raise it upon
								the ruins of all the rest;

And your foot on the neck of the menacing one, the

     scorner,
								utterly crush'd beneath you;

The menacing, arrogant one, that strode and advanced
with his senseless scorn, bearing the murderous
knife;

29 Of all races and eras, These States, with veins full of
poetical stuff, most need poets, and are to have
the greatest, and use them the greatest;

In war, he is the best backer of the war — he fetches
artillery as good as the engineer's — he can
make every word he speaks draw blood;

He judges not as the judge judges, but as the sun

     falling round
								a helpless thing;

The battle-front forms amid the smoke — the volleys

     pour
								incessant from the line;

Admirers, importers, obedient persons, make but the

     soil of
								literature;

People's lips salute only doers, lovers, satisfiers,

     positive
								knowers;

Are your body, days, manners, superb? after death

     you shall be
								superb;

I swear I will stand by my own nativity — pious or

     impious, so
								be it;

I saw you serenely give birth to children — saw in

     dreams your
								dilating form;

And that there is no flaw or vacuum in the amount of
the truth — but that all is truth without ex-
ception;

Splendid suns, the moons and rings, the countless

     combinations
								and effects;

1 WHAT am I, after all, but a child, pleased with the
sound of my own name? repeating it over and
over;

How America illustrates birth, gigantic youth, the
promise, the sure fulfilment, despite of people
— Illustrates evil as well as good;

How many hold despairingly yet to the models de-
parted, caste, myths, obedience, compulsion, and
to infidelity;

How the whirl, the contest, the wrestle of evil with
good, the sounding and resounding, keep on
and on;

How society waits unform'd, and is between things

     ended and
								things begun;

Of what a few years will show there in Nebraska,

     Colorado,
								Nevada, and the rest;

Of what the feuillage of America is the preparation
for — and of what all the sights, North, South,
East and West, are;

Of future men and women there — of happiness in
those high plateaus, ranging three thousand
miles, warm and cold;

Of a free and original life there — of simple diet and

     clean and
								sweet blood;

Of litheness, majestic faces, clear eyes, and perfect

     physique
								there;

Of immense spiritual results, future years, each side

     of the
								Anahuacs;

Illustrious the mystery of motion, in all beings, even

     the tiniest
							insect;

As I went forth in the morning — As I beheld the light

     breaking in the
							east;

As I bathed on the beach of the Eastern Sea, and

     again on the
							beach of the Western Sea;

As I roam'd the streets of inland Chicago — whatever

     streets I have
							roam'd;

Who have explored the outward, the surfaces of the

     races
							— the life that has exhibited itself;

Who have treated of man as the creature of politics,

     aggregates,
							rulers and priests;

I do not doubt but the majesty and beauty of the

     world are latent
							in any iota of the world;

I do not doubt I am limitless, and that the universes

     are limitless
							— in vain I try to think how limitless;

I do not doubt that temporary affairs keep on and on,

     millions of
							years;

I do not doubt that cities, you, America, the remain-
der of the earth, politics, freedom, degrada-
tions, are carefully provided for;
